<HEADLINE>
<P>
PREP BASEBALL ROUNDUP; GOLISANO GETS HAPPY BY SHUTTING OUT TROY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS FOSTER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Pitcher Ryan Golisano had been in a slump. 
</P>
<P>
 True, he had consecutive victories that kept Fullerton one step ahead of the 
crowd in the Freeway League. But Golisano was not happy about it. 
</P>
<P>
 "I wasn't throwing enough strikes," Golisano said. "I was walking too many 
batters and making too many mistakes. They were just bad outings." 
</P>
<P>
 Golisano found satisfaction Wednesday, pitching a three-hitter to beat Troy, 
4-0, at Fullerton, keeping the Indians in first place. 
</P>
<P>
 It was Golisano's first shutout of the season, and a performance that left 
Troy Coach Dane Ilertsen shaking his head in admiration. 
</P>
<P>
 "We could have played all day and not beaten him,," Ilertsen said. "His 
fastball was fast, his slider was sliding and his splitter was splitting. 
Everything did what it was supposed to do." 
</P>
<P>
 Golisano (10-1) struck out only two, but he was nearly unhittable. He retired 
10 of the last 12 batters he faced. 
</P>
<P>
 The Warriors (14-7, 7-5) hit only five balls out of the infield. 
</P>
<P>
 Golisano had labored since losing to Sunny Hills three weeks ago. He had won 
but had not looked good doing so. 
</P>
<P>
 "Ryan hadn't been going at hitters," Coach Dolf Hes said. "He needed to be 
more aggressive." 
</P>
<P>
 He was. Troy had opportunities early, but Golisano hung tough. 
</P>
<P>
 The Warriors loaded the bases with two outs in the second, but Rich Richey's 
line drive was snagged by second baseman Steve St. Pierre. In the third, Troy 
had two on with one out, but Golisano got two weak popups to wiggle out. 
</P>
<P>
 The Indians (17-5, 9-3) provided some offense, but not a lot. Troy's Rick 
Parmenter (5-3) pitched a strong game but made a few mistakes. 
</P>
<P>
 The Indians got three consecutive hits, including RBI singles by Craig Freeman 
and Ryan Schatz, to take a 2-0 lead in the third. They also got a home run by 
Keith Ginter in the fifth and a run-scoring single by pinch-hitter Matt Sanders 
in the sixth. CHRIS FOSTER 
</P>
</TEXT>
