<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: CAMARILLO; GROUP SEEKS TO FIGHT CITY'S SMOKING BAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By J.E. MITCHELL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A group of smokers' rights advocates opposed to Camarillo's recently adopted 
smoking ordinance is preparing to distribute petitions seeking to place the new 
law before city voters during November's municipal election. 
</P>
<P>
 According to Pat Johnson, owner of Lil' Bit O' Country on Daily Drive and a 
spokeswoman for the group, the petition forms were being finished at a local 
printing company Wednesday.She said they should be ready for the group by 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 "We are ready to go with this," Johnson said. "We feel this is a 
personal-rights issue and that the City Council far overstepped its authority 
in passing this ordinance. We're hoping to start the drive this Friday." 
</P>
<P>
 At its meeting last Wednesday, the council voted 3 to 2 to approve the 
ordinance, which largely bans smoking in restaurants and public places. 
</P>
<P>
 Camarillo City Clerk Marilyn Thiel said the group must collect at least 2,937 
signatures, or 10% of the city's registered voters to place a referendum on the 
ballot. If the group is successful, the City Council would first have 30 days 
to rescind the ordinance. 
</P>
<P>
 Thiel said the group has until May 27 to collect the required number of 
signatures. Otherwise, the council's ordinance will become law on that date. 
J.E. MITCHELL 
</P>
</TEXT>
